AMCAT Data Analysis¶

AMCAT (Aspiring Minds Computer Adaptive Test) is an employability assessment test used by companies to evaluate the job-readiness of candidates. The test assesses various skills such as aptitude, technical knowledge, and communication skills.

out_dict={}
for i in col:
    Q1 = df[i].quantile(0.05)
    Q3 = df[i].quantile(0.95)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    outliers = df[(df[i] < lower_bound) | (df[i] > upper_bound)]
    out_dict[i]=outliers

from fuzzywuzzy import process

def correct_spelling_errors(target_word="", choices=[], threshold=80):
    match, score = process.extractOne(target_word, choices)
    if score >= threshold:
        return match
    else:
        return target_word

# Is there a relationship between gender and specialization? (i.e. Does the preference of Specialisation depend on the Gender?)

from scipy.stats import chi2
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

x = np.linspace(0, 100, 100)
y = chi2.pdf(x, df = 4)
plt.plot(x, y)

obsr = pd.crosstab(df.Specialization,df.Gender)
obsr

chi2_statistic, chi2_p_value, chi2_dof, chi2_expected = chi2_contingency(obsr)

print("Statistic            :", chi2_statistic)
print('')
print("p value              :", chi2_p_value)
print('')
print("Degrees of freedom   :", chi2_dof)
print('')
print("Expected frequencies array:\n", chi2_expected)

confidence_level = 0.95
alpha = 1 - confidence_level
chi2_critical = chi2.ppf(1 - alpha, chi2_dof)
chi2_critical

x_min = -10
x_max = 100

x = np.linspace(x_min, x_max, 100)
y = chi2.pdf(x, chi2_dof)
plt.xlim(x_min, x_max)
plt.plot(x, y)

chi2_critical_right = chi2_critical
x1 = np.linspace(chi2_critical_right, x_max, 100)
y1 = chi2.pdf(x1, chi2_dof)
plt.fill_between(x1, y1, color='green')

if(chi2_statistic > chi2_critical):
    print("There is not enough evidence to reject the Null Hypothesis")
else:
    print("There is sufficent evidence to reject the Null Hypothesis")

if(chi2_p_value < alpha):
    print("There is not enough evidence to reject the Null Hypothesis")
else:
    print("There is sufficent evidence to reject the Null Hypothesis")

observed = pd.crosstab(df['Specialization'], df['Gender'])

chi2_statistic, chi2_p_value, chi2_dof, chi2_expected = chi2_contingency(observed)

print("Statistic            :", chi2_statistic)
print("p value              :", chi2_p_value)
print("Degrees of freedom   :", chi2_dof)
print("Expected frequencies array:\n", chi2_expected)

confidence_level = 0.95
alpha = 1 - confidence_level
chi2_critical = chi2.ppf(1 - alpha, chi2_dof)

x = np.linspace(0, 30, 1000)
plt.plot(x, chi2.pdf(x, chi2_dof), label='Chi-Square Distribution')
plt.fill_between(x, 0, chi2.pdf(x, chi2_dof), where=(x > chi2_critical), color='orange', alpha=0.5, label='Critical Region')

if chi2_statistic > chi2_critical:
    print("There is not enough evidence to reject the Null Hypothesis based on the critical value.")
else:
    print("There is sufficient evidence to reject the Null Hypothesis based on the critical value.")

if chi2_p_value < alpha:
    print("There is not enough evidence to reject the Null Hypothesis based on the p-value.")
else:
    print("There is sufficient evidence to reject the Null Hypothesis based on the p-value.")

plt.legend()
plt.xlabel('Chi-Square Value')
plt.ylabel('Probability Density')
plt.title('Chi-Square Distribution and Critical Region')
plt.show()
